[0m[49m[39m  300, 300[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Identity boundaries per component.** The cross-facility pipeline has four trust-boundary-sensitive components, each with its own identity posture. The inbound-query handler validates the requesting organization's identity through mTLS or signed JWT, verifies the asserted purpose-of-use against the participation agreement, and rate-limits per requester to prevent enumeration attacks. The outbound-query submitter signs queries with the institutional credential and verifies response signatures from participating organizations. The consent-and-sensitivity filter is the most security-sensitive component: it reads consent state from the consent-registry-of-record (not from a cache that may be stale on consent revocation) and fails closed (if the consent registry is unavailable, withhold release rather than release). The audit-log writer uses append-only, signature-chained writes replicated to a separate audit account; tampering attempts surface immediately. Same chapter pattern as recipes 5.1, 5.2, 5.3, 5.4 Finding S1.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-recipe event contract.** Cross-facility match events propagate to downstream consumers via a standardized schema: `source`, `detail_type`, `detail.local_patient_id`, `detail.cross_org_identifier`, `detail.event_id`, `detail.previous_state`, `detail.new_state`, `detail.detected_at`. Downstream consumers include: recipe 5.1 (local matcher; a cross-facility match may surface a previously-unknown duplicate-patient signal locally), recipe 5.4 (eligibility matcher; cross-facility match data may inform a payer-side identity question), recipe 5.6 (claims-clinical linkage; cross-facility identifier may help bridge claim-vs-clinical join), recipe 5.7 (longitudinal name-change matcher; cross-facility queries are a common surfacing point for prior-name records), recipe 5.8 (privacy-preserving linkage; cross-facility identifier resolution interacts with the privacy-preserving layer), plus the longitudinal-record-assembler, the patient-portal access-report generator, and the consent-management workflow. Each consumer subscribes to specific `detail_type` values and acknowledges processing via a CloudWatch metric (`{consumer}.events_processed`). Same chapter pattern as recipes 5.1, 5.2, 5.3, 5.4.
